  RFC4379 [label="RFC4379
Detecting Multi-Protocol Label Switched
(MPLS) Data Plane Failures
2006", shape=ellipse, URL="RFC4379.html", target="_top", tooltip="This document describes a simple and efficient mechanism that can be used to detect data plane failures in Multi-Protocol Label Switching (MPLS) Label Switched Paths (LSPs).  There are two parts to this document: information carried in an MPLS echo request and echo reply for the purposes of fault detection and isolation, and mechanisms for reliably sending the echo reply. [STANDARDS-TRACK]"];
  RFC4379 -> rev_cites;
  RFC4925 [label="RFC4925
Softwire Problem Statement
2007", shape=ellipse, URL="RFC4925.html", target="_top", tooltip="This document captures the problem statement for the Softwires Working Group, which is developing standards for the discovery, control, and encapsulation methods for connecting IPv4 networks across IPv6-only networks as well as IPv6 networks across IPv4-only networks.  The standards will encourage multiple, inter-operable vendor implementations by identifying, and extending where necessary, existing standard protocols to resolve a selected set of IPv4/IPv6 and IPv6/IPv4 transition problems.  This document describes the specific problems (Hubs and Spokes and Mesh) that will be solved by the standards developed by the Softwires Working Group.  Some requirements (and non-requirements) are also identified to better describe the specific problem scope.  This memo provides information for the Internet community."];
  RFC4925 -> rev_cites;
  RFC6513 [label="RFC6513
Multicast in MPLS/BGP IP VPNs
2012", shape=ellipse, URL="RFC6513.html", target="_top", tooltip="In order for IP multicast traffic within a BGP/MPLS IP VPN (Virtual Private Network) to travel from one VPN site to another, special protocols and procedures must be implemented by the VPN Service Provider.  These protocols and procedures are specified in this document. [STANDARDS-TRACK]"];
  RFC6513 -> rev_cites;
  RFC8029 [label="RFC8029
Detecting Multiprotocol Label Switched
(MPLS) Data-Plane Failures
2017", shape=ellipse, URL="RFC8029.html", target="_top", tooltip="This document describes a simple and efficient mechanism to detect data-plane failures in Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) Label Switched Paths (LSPs). It defines a probe message called an MPLS echo request and a response message called an MPLS echo reply for returning the result of the probe. The MPLS echo request is intended to contain sufficient information to check correct operation of the data plane and to verify the data plane against the control plane, thereby localizing faults. This document obsoletes RFCs 4379, 6424, 6829, and 7537, and updates RFC 1122."];
  RFC8029 -> rev_cites;
  RFC9135 [label="RFC9135
Integrated Routing and Bridging in
Ethernet VPN (EVPN)
2021", shape=ellipse, URL="RFC9135.html", target="_top", tooltip="Ethernet VPN (EVPN) provides an extensible and flexible multihoming VPN solution over an MPLS/IP network for intra-subnet connectivity among Tenant Systems and end devices that can be physical or virtual.  However, there are scenarios for which there is a need for a dynamic and efficient inter-subnet connectivity among these Tenant Systems and end devices while maintaining the multihoming capabilities of EVPN.  This document describes an Integrated Routing and Bridging (IRB) solution based on EVPN to address such requirements."];
  RFC9135 -> rev_cites;
  RFC9889 [label="RFC9889
A Realization of Network Slices for 5G
Networks Using Current IP/MPLS
Technologies
2025", shape=ellipse, URL="RFC9889.html", target="_top", tooltip="Network slicing is a feature that was introduced by the 3rd Generation Partnership Project (3GPP) in Mobile Networks. Realization of 5G slicing implies requirements for all mobile domains, including the Radio Access Network (RAN), Core Network (CN), and Transport Network (TN). This document describes a network slice realization model for IP/MPLS networks with a focus on the Transport Network fulfilling the service objectives for 5G slicing connectivity. The realization model reuses many building blocks commonly used in service provider networks at the current time."];
  RFC9889 -> rev_cites;
